segments.text: This is an interview with Mr. Virgil Gay by Wanda Marison Masek in 1994 at the Northgate Parking Garage, 2nd floor, concerning black awareness in the 1960s and early 70s.
In the interest of accumulating knowledge about this, I am going to donate this tape to Texane and Oral History Collection in the University Archives.
I was born in what they call Third Ward area.

And, you know, you had, in front of the hamburger stand, these were walk-up windows.
They had white on the other side to color.
And so to sit there in a car and watch your dad go up to the color side and buy some hamburgers and come back and eat and go, you know, kind of thing.
So, you know, you knew it was there, although it really didn't necessarily affect you right where you lived.
